segments.text: One of the things I can think of is that we were trying to get a street maintenance program going, a renovation program, and I submitted it to Robert and never

never could get it could get it going that and the the landscape rejuvenation program was another one that I think probably was landscape rejuvenation program I was trying I was trying to get some this was to Cargill I remember now because they'd come out with

saying that you could use the available fund monies for this and that and all and so I'd been thinking about it and I sat down and wrote up a, I don't know, probably a four or five page squib on why I cited some specific examples of buildings and this kind of thing that we had to
had to do as well as the irrigation stuff.
We were getting to the point where a lot of our irrigation systems needed renovation and we needed to go to another control system.
And one thing I might mention too that I'm kind of proud of,
And as part of all this development, the irrigation systems got to mounting up, and we got to the point that we had more irrigation systems going than we could turn off when it rained.
And Mike and I had talked about some way to handle it, and he'd looked into see if there were anything available, and there wasn't anything available readily on the market.
And then one day, after one of our summers like this, and hired vessels coming into work,
And he was coming around the North Durham area and the sprinklers were going and it was raining.
And I got a call.
And he said, cut the damn sprinklers off.
And I said, we are, Mr. Vestal.
It takes about four man days to cut just to switch the things off.
He said, we need to fix that.
And I said, we're working on it.
So Goldwater and I got busy and we got to talking about it.
And we were talking to Motorola at the time about a new radio system, two-way.
And we got to talking to him a little bit more and and.
And that's where Goldwater came in.
I mean he he's got a real inquisitive mind.
And the upshot was that Motorola had developed a switch.
That they had installed on a number of residential hot water heaters.
In Central Arkansas, some power grid or power company over there.
And they did that, and they kept, they would switch hot water heaters randomly on and off, you know.
And by doing that, they saved building a power plant.
Okay.
So we got to talking about, well, could we take something like that,

and incorporated in our existing controllers and so we got to working with motorola folks and then got the toro folks came into it because they had what they call their golf course control system which was a bank of i think six big controllers
Anyway, the upshot was we were able to take and modify our existing controllers and we designed a console and board that had 36 switches.
Yeah.
And I had 30 switches because we got a radio system that was a non-voice control system and that would generate 30 coded tones.
And so the upshot was we would put a tone read and some relays in our existing, we did all this in-house in our existing controllers, and then a radio switch up on that thing.
And we could control, we got to the point where we could, we had six master clocks, and we could, by a series of switches, we could control

switch it to one clock or another, switch it off or whatever, and we got to the point where we could turn everything on remotely by radio, and if, let's say, and we put what we called a black box in the physical plant radio room, so that if there was a fire or something of that nature, they could flip a switch and in 30 seconds, all the extraneous water was off.
And we had to use that when Penn State came to play here because lightning knocked out every well in the well field.
And all the water we had was in the tower.
But, and that ultimately became, Motorola and Total kept doing that, and they've now got one that has feedback.
I mean, it's got all kinds of bells and whistles.
But that's where all that got started.
And ours was getting kind of old.
We were trying to

upgrade upgrade that to you know much much better level but uh and we had it tied into a rain stat that we could set it for a quarter half an inch and it would shut everything down automatically and that solved howard's problem in comparison to the campus proper now i'm not talking about the ag experiment fields about what percentage of the water usage as far as you know during those years
was used in grounds maintenance?
How much water was used in flower beds and grass and trees?
I think it was...
Compared to the rest of the campus usage?
Probably about 40 percent, because I think, no about 30 percent, because I think we figured one time on
on all of our tap valves and what it would run, and we were using about a million gallons to a million and a half gallons every time we watered.
How could we have done campus planning better from the landscape, from the grounds maintenance?
It would have been, I think, better if there had been some more long-range stuff done so that you had, because so many of the master plans.
Now, the West Campus came about pretty good because Strickland-Rollins did a master plan.
That was followed reasonably well.
But most of the other master plans kind of got put up on the shelf.
And no one was ever pushing to get it implemented, you know.
Having been here, having gotten here 41 years ago, I think this campus looks unplanned.
It does.
The architecture is inconsistent.
And Paul Stevens and I used to have some real hard arguments.
I kept saying, we need some continuity in buildings.
He said, well, the architecture's dying.
I said, well, who the hell does he work for?
You know.
And it was about that time that at least they settled on a consistent brick.
That was a step.
But no, I think there needed to be some planning standards.
And each architect got that, just like they got the Red Book.
And these are your boundaries.
And Paul says, no, you can't give them boundaries.
And I said, well, you can't let them build something that's a monument to their own being.
And that's essentially what's happened with a lot of the buildings, I think.
Typist, this also does need to be put in there.
When I got to UT El Paso 20 years ago right now, the architecture out there is copied after the little nation of Bhutan up in the Himalayas near Nepal.
Oh.
building on the campus is that style.
And one of my great accomplishments was a new library building, $28 million.
And the guidelines we gave to the architectural firm, the first three principles were it must be Bhutanese, it must be Bhutanese, it must be Bhutanese.
Then next is we want as much building per dollar as we can get.
And the next point is it must be expandable
in each of the four directions horizontally and it must be expandable vertically.
Expandable vertically.
Yeah.
Don't have to go down.
You've got to go, because we don't know how libraries are going.
And we got a building including furnishings for $80 a square foot.
Wow.
And he finished six months ahead of schedule.
Wow.
And it works superbly.
Yeah.
So it could be done.
Let's see.

Among the realities that A&M, correct me if I'm wrong, among the realities that A&M must cope with in terms of grounds maintenance and so forth is we do have one of the most difficult locations in terms of oil and climate.
Yes, without question.
I know Bob Rucki said that's the reason they put A&M here.
But the soil is a problem and the water is an even bigger problem.

and the soil can be with organic matter and this kind of thing you can you can kind of work around that a little bit but the water problem is you just got to wait on mother nature to leach it out as far as you know if we went deeper for our water wells could we get better water that i don't know it would probably be hotter i guess but i i really
know I just don't know because I haven't been on in on many of those many of those discussions.
All right let's see now we're going to try to summarize things of which you're great most proud most greatest successes.
Oh I think that during all the

real building and and all like this is that we kept the campus looking looking very good and that we were able to i think change some ideas particularly with the staff about you know and and create some

um intensity about hey this is looking good you know and it it it's something that grows it's it's like i mentioned the garden area system you've got one real good garden over here another one over here that's maybe not quite as good and he's always looking over there seeing what the other guy's doing maybe i need to do that and that kind of thing and it's it's something that that that builds a pride because when i got here our folks didn't have any pride
They just, because they were afraid if they did something, they'd get torn up.
Examples you can remember where somebody bothered to take the time to show some appreciation for the work y'all had done?
Oh, yeah.
I've got some nice notes from people like O.D.
Butler, some Howard Vestal's one, and there may be some from some of the presidents.
Perry Atkinson, you know, a number of folks like that.
Any off-campus visitors, notes or comments you remember?
Yeah, I can't think of who.
Governors?
No, don't think we had any comments from any of the governors.
All right, now that causes me to think, did y'all have any involvement in the Bush Library dream?

a little bit I didn't have any involvement in uh... in the planning because that was in the Joe Sugg era when I didn't get any looks at the reviews or anything like that but uh... the in the last three months of that I lived out there because I was the liaison between uh... the contractor facilities planning and the university as far as
particularly outside and some of the inside, and I was trying to help the Bush School.
They were having problems with the building.
That's 96, 97?
This, well, it was, no, it was 90, yeah, 97, 97, because it was...

probably from july until the building the building was dedicated and uh that's that's basically all i did is finally i went i went to joe ester and i said look we've got to get this outside you need to give us a work order and tell the contractor to scoot and he did and we got it ready you know for the dedication uh special moments that you remember
specific moments of joy, pride?
I don't know when I look out and look at all the trees that we planted and because probably every tree under 15 or 16 inches in diameter
been planted since 1973.
And being able to, you know, kind of delineate the campus and the streets and this kind of thing.
I don't know, we always tried to make the landscape as the, try and think of the term, kind of the glue that held everything together, basically.
as well as, you know, create a positive impression.
And in a kind of a sentimental link there, I heard Bob Rucker told me that he helped water the first trees out toward the new East Gate when he was an undergraduate.
Yeah.
Low moments, sad moments?
Oh, I guess when we were suffering some budget cuts and then when the merger occurred.
That was probably the worst.
And I guess one of the problems is I'd never had anything like that.
I mean, that was totally new ground, you know, because until, probably until, I believe after Robert took over a little bit, but for 16 or 17 years,
I had probably the best ground jobs in the country without any question.
And I would have, we had people from Tech and Oklahoma and several other schools that would come to kind of see how we did it, you know.
And they have, as an example, Tech and OU have now broken their grounds out.
And Randy Lacewell at OU reports directly to the president.
He reports directly to David Boren.
He called me up and he said, he wants me to report directly to him.
What am I gonna do?
I said, Randy, you can't beat that.
I said, jump on it and run.
He said, well, I just hope I can outlast the physical plant man.
Of all those years, to whom would you most want to express appreciation if all of them were still alive and could be brought here?
Probably would be number one, Bob Rucker, and number two, Tom Cherry.
You know, the rest of them were great, no question about it.
But those two...
Put it into words, why?
Well, without those two, I wouldn't have been here.
Just that simple.
And without Bob Rucker, I wouldn't have been in this field.
I don't know what I'd be doing now.
Did he help attract you to major in?
No.
They had a program.
You know, I was a dumb kid from a small town.
And so everybody else was majoring in business, so I thought, hey, I will too, you know.
And so we had to take some science.
And I'd grown up in a hatchery and feed store, and I had a small nursery.
and had done a lot of stuff on the side out of the little nursery area.
So I started to register for classes, and you could take horticulture as a science.
Hey, I know a little bit about that, I'll do that.
And then I found out that economics and I didn't agree and so after the first semester I switched to horticulture and then Bob came and we

I had a class under him that I had landscape design and then I guess the last couple of years he was there I worked myself and another friend of mine, we worked for him for registration and that was neat because we got to pre-register, we got our classes like we wanted it, you know, as well as making a little money too and all.
That's kind of how I got over there, because my mother was always a big garden clubber, and we'd had this little nursery, and I'd done a lot of yard work and a lot of stuff like that.
And I guess if it hadn't been for that, I'd still been trying to major in business.
I don't know.
Let's make believe that you were hired as the consultant to A&M today.
Mm-hmm.
If you were a consultant on the grounds maintenance landscaping effort, what advice would you give them?
Well, the first thing, they're going to have to spend some money because you cannot keep adding acres and acres and acres and expect it to look class A.
Second thing they need to do is they need to develop some zones of maintenance.
At one point in time we had four, class A, B, C, and D. D being like roadways and infrequence and all like that.
Class A being MSC, rudder tower, president's home, library, administration building, the real heart and core of the campus, that kind of thing.
and that they need to do a little better job in their training.
One of the problems that I think they've experienced is that, and I probably shouldn't rag on Joe Sugg, but his idea of a grounds maintenance was an old boy and a lawn mower to pick up.

and what one of the things that happened with our irrigation as an example he basically did away for a while with the control system and every gardener was operating their own system and water was coming on anywhere anytime and it was all getting screwed up and everything until finally they were able to get a hold of it when i was in the director well mike and i got together and we
got it going back where we were using the automated system and only a few people did the programming because you just can't

you can't have 125 or 30 controllers and you know I mean it's just you might have every controller in one corner of the campus go and then you don't have any water for the rest you know it just because you can't distribute your water you're equalizing the distribution of your water but uh now I think the money's that and people need to be educated that
to do the job like people would like it to be done, it's a costly endeavor, and it takes some trained people.
You can't do it with laboring folks.
I mean, you need some of those, but you've got to have some other folks that have the knowledge and expertise to do the scheduling and help the people and train them and this kind of thing.
Organizationally, it should report?
It should report to the vice president.
Vice president.
Yeah.
And geographically, for what area should it be responsible?
Basically everything outside the buildings?
No, no.
Oh, any of the public here right now, I think they've got the responsibility of just about everything from Texas Avenue to 2818.
And that's all come about with Bush Library because see there was a lot of area between the library and the research park that of necessity had to be.
But they have that, they have the research park now too.
Yeah.
Oh yeah, we've had the research park since from the very beginning.
At Easterwood Airport too.
Uh-huh.
And from the front of the terminal building and out.
Veterinary Medicine.
I'm not sure how those are handled now, but I know at one point in time we did.
Another thing I'm proud of too is, I talked to Jerry about this, but after the library came in and we see it was coming about, it appeared to me that

we needed to protect some of the area so I went up to Jerry and talked to him and asked him if he minded me working on some of this and I talked to probably a dozen people on campus from dean of agriculture down to forest science, horticulture, rain science, intramurals, rec sports and the upshot was
And I gave it to Jerry, and he took it to the board.
We got the area along the creek from horticulture down through the library set back, because I could just see some engineers saying, we can build across that.
And my premise was that it was time to hold something back for green area instead of taking it away.
Would that be an appropriate area for a kind of a natural?
Yes, an arboretum and all like this.
I mean, that would be superb.

Oh, yeah, yeah, and that's what, and I think they're beginning, I talked to Sam Cotner the other day, and I think they're beginning to work on that, and I want to try to be involved in it, because that's something that's really near and dear to me, because I think it'd be really great to have something that you could take some kids out from a lecture and look at the real thing, or
a visitor coming to campus would like to look at a specific plant or something like this and see what it really looks like in full living, breathing color, you know.
But we're one of the few land grant universities that does not have anything of that nature.
And it's going to cost some money.
But a lot of it could be done from industry.
where they would give and then give some maintenance subsidy and this kind of thing, I think.
But that took a lot of work, because I did the tree inventory for the library.
Joe Sugg came in to staff me one day, and he said, he turned to the assistant director that Grounds reported to, and he said, I want you to send a gardener out there and identify all the trees.
And I said, I don't mean to interrupt, but you need somebody more than a gardener.
And he said, well, you're so damn smart, you go do it.
I said, okay.
It got me out of the office.
Of course, it was in August, about like it was now.
But there's some magnificent trees and terrain down in there.
It could be, there are just a lot of things.
Without a great deal of work, you know, there's water oaks down there that big, monstrous trees.
Is there some kind of natural spring that feeds that little gullet?
Oh, there's not any water that runs all the time?
Well, most of it's drainage water from campus because it comes all the way down from, in fact, that drainage way originates over east of, across the university and east of the Entomology Field Lab.
That's where it originates.
Really?
And I don't know whether you remember, but
before they built the med school, there was a huge gully that went down through there.
And all that's underground.
In fact, the business or the med school library and the business school, they're setting a straddle of those big box corporates, I think.
Somebody the other day from off campus tried to tell me that
Wolfpin Creek drains there.
No.
Now, Wolfpin Creek picks up about the library power plant and on down.
Okay, I've got two questions.
Somebody walks up to you and gives you a million dollars, a million-dollar check with one restriction.
You must pass it on to Texas A&M, and you decide the purpose of the gift.
What would you have to do with it?
It's pretty easy.
A portion of it would go to the Greenway to get it started.
And I think probably some of it would go to help the grounds.
And then I think there needs to be some scholarships endowed for ornamental horticulture.
And on what basis would the students in that major be selected?
Oh, there would have to be some need involved, but there'd also have to be some desire involved.
You know, it's needs one thing and desires another thing.
If you can get the need and the desire together, the better.
Because you would like if someone goes to school, you know, and gets a degree that they're going to use it.
Because I know I have classmates that went into insurance and a lot of different things.
They didn't use their degree, and I think that's a waste.
All right, now I've just got one question left.
Have we not covered something that you thought of in advance that we should have?
I can't think of anything.
I really can't.
Last question is, what feelings do you have in your heart for Texas A&M today?
Well, I'm probably more of an Aggie than I am a Red Raider.
I've never seen a place where the former students supported like they do.
And I thought I'd seen that at Oklahoma.
Of course, that was more for football, I guess.
But Aggies support it.
There's just no argument about it.
